dataIdInfo.idAbs:
This tool measures terrain ruggedness as the variation in three-dimensional orientation of grid cells within a neighborhood. Vector analysis is used to calculate the dispersion of vectors normal (orthogonal) to grid cells within the specified neighborhood. This method effectively captures variability in slope and aspect into a single measure. Ruggedness values in the output raster can range from 0 (no terrain variation) to 1 (complete terrain variation). Typical values for natural terrains range between 0 and about 0.4.

This script is adapted in part from an ArcGIS 9 version created by Mark Sappington.

tool.name: terrainruggedness

param.name: Neighborhood_Size
param.dialogReference: Neighborhood size for the ruggedness calculation. Value must be an integer and should be odd (e.g. 3, 5, 21, etc.). Smaller neighborhoods measure ruggedness within more localized areas whereas larger neighborhoods measure ruggedness over greater landscape areas.
param.pythonReference: Neighborhood size for the ruggedness calculation. Value must be an integer and should be odd (e.g. 3, 5, 21, etc.). Smaller neighborhoods measure ruggedness within more localized areas whereas larger neighborhoods measure ruggedness over greater landscape areas.

param.name: Temporary_Workspace
param.dialogReference: A temporary location for storing the intermediate steps in the VRM calculation.
param.pythonReference: A temporary location for storing the intermediate steps in the VRM calculation.

param.name: Output_Raster
param.dialogReference: Name and output workspace (folder or geodatabase) for the final raster.
param.pythonReference: Name and output workspace (folder or geodatabase) for the final raster.

scriptExample.title: Running from the command line
scriptExample.para:
This script can also be invoked directly from the command-line directly, with the parameters passed as arguments to the script:

python ruggedness.py <bathymetry raster> <neighborhood size> <workspace path> <output raster>
